  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-content">
      <article class="content-article">
        <h2>What Is an ATS Resume Scanner and Why You Need It</h2>
        <p>An ATS (Applicant Tracking System) resume scanner simulates how hiring software parses and interprets your resume. When you submit a job application online, it rarely goes directly to a recruiter. Instead, an ATS scans your resume, extracts key information, and stores it in a structured database. If the system cannot correctly parse your name, contact details, work history, or skills, your application may be silently filtered out before any human lays eyes on it.</p>

        <p>Our free ATS resume preview tool gives you a behind-the-scenes look at this process. By pasting your resume text and scanning it, you can see exactly what an ATS extracts — and what it misses. This transparency helps you identify parsing problems before they cost you an opportunity.</p>

        <h3>How ATS Parsing Works</h3>
        <p>ATS parsing software looks for patterns in your resume to categorize information. It scans for email formats, phone number patterns, location strings, and LinkedIn URLs in the contact section. It identifies section headings by matching common labels like "Experience," "Education," and "Skills." It extracts skills by comparing words against a database of known technical and professional competencies. The parsed data is then presented to recruiters as a clean, structured profile — but only if the parser processes your resume correctly.</p>

        <p>Common parsing failures include content placed in headers or footers (ATS often skips these), information inside tables or multiple columns (the parser reads left-to-right, top-to-bottom and jumbles the order), graphics and icons (most ATS systems ignore them entirely), and non-standard section headings (if the parser doesn't recognize a heading, that content may be lumped into the wrong category).</p>

        <h3>What Our Resume Scanner Reveals</h3>
        <p>Our scanner extracts and displays four critical pieces of information from your resume. <strong>Contact Information:</strong> Name, email address, phone number, and location. If any of these are missing or incorrectly parsed, recruiters cannot reach you. <strong>Skills Detected:</strong> A list of skills the ATS identifies in your resume. Comparing this against the job description reveals keyword gaps. <strong>Section Headers Found:</strong> Which resume sections the ATS recognizes. Standard headers like Experience, Education, and Skills get full credit; creative headers may go undetected. <strong>Raw Text Rendering:</strong> A pure-text version of your resume showing how the ATS sees it after stripping formatting. This reveals exactly what information gets lost or scrambled.</p>

        <p>Alongside the extraction results, the scanner flags common issues: missing contact information, no clear section headers, low word count, lack of quantified bullet points, or potential table-based formatting. Each issue includes a suggestion for how to fix it.</p>

        <h3>How to Prepare an ATS-Friendly Resume</h3>
        <p>Start by running your current resume through our scanner. Review the raw text rendering — if the order of your information looks wrong, you likely have a formatting issue. Check that all five elements of your contact information are extracted. Look for your key skills in the skills list; if they are missing, they may not be in a format the ATS recognizes. Make sure every standard section (Summary, Experience, Education, Skills) is detected. Address any flagged issues one by one. Use standard section headings, avoid tables and columns, put all important content in the main document body, and use a clean single-column layout. Pair your ATS-optimized resume with our <a href="/ats-score">ATS Score Checker</a> for a detailed compatibility analysis across five dimensions.</p>

        <p>A resume optimized for ATS parsing not only passes the machine screening — it also presents cleaner, more organized information to recruiters when they open your full profile. Check your <a href="/ats-score">ATS compatibility score</a> and explore our <a href="/resume-examples">industry-specific resume examples</a> for templates that are designed to parse cleanly.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="capture reveal">
    <div class="capture-inner">
      <h3>Weekly Resume Tips, Straight to Your Inbox</h3>
      <p>Join 12,000+ job seekers getting expert ATS advice, keyword strategies, and career insights.</p>
      <form class="capture-form" onsubmit="event.preventDefault()">
        <input type="email" placeholder="your@email.com" required />
        <button type="submit">Subscribe</button>
      </form>
